segments.text: Okay, we can continue.
The Southern Education Board was a forerunner of many regional boards which made provisions for students in states that had no veterinary school to attend veterinary school in nearby states.
For example, the Southern School took care of
Most of the students in the South, they could either go to Georgia, Alabama, or Texas, depending on which was the nearest.
The Western schools included Colorado and Washington and so forth.
The Northern schools mostly were in, I mean, the North Central schools primarily went to Iowa
Northeastern schools to Cornell.
Even this didn't take care of the students, so many states made provision for veterinary schools their own.
For example, Minnesota, Virginia, Louisiana, Mississippi, California,
Oh, I don't know.
I can't call them all, but all those... California Davis?
Yes.
All those fuels came in after World War II.
So the curriculum was pretty well standardized, and you had to have so many hours, you can get that in the catalog.
But that's pretty well standardized, regardless of what fuel you go to in the United States.
There may be a little variation, for example, in the number of hours traded, or due to the

Location that may be more emphasis like we have more emphasis on Ferris dog in Texas than they do on in Minnesota, for example, while they have Maybe One on the disease of fur-bearing animals, which it's a little consequence here.
Yes, but all in all the curriculum was first established by the National Defense Act of 1920 and
when it set out the requirements for a veterinarian that was entitled to or competent to be employed by the federal government.
And during the Depression years, this was particularly important because many veterinarians left their practice to seek government work in order to make ends meet.
Now, I have a question concerning the increasing number of pre-professional college work.
In 1975, or after the Second World War, you had to have basically two hours or two years of pre-professional.
And in 1975 at Texas A&M, it was increased to 66 hours.
Today, do you need a BS degree officially to gain entrance into Texas A&M?
I don't know.

okay I retired 10 years ago yeah 11 years ago I really don't know and the basic and could you and the basic reason as I understand for an increase in in the number of hours before you get into vet school is to make better vet students and because the competition was too high are those the two reasons well and and to get everything possible out of the
veterinary college proper that could be taught in other places.
In other words, like English, or physics, or entomology, or chemistry, or biological chemistry.
There's many things like that that can be better taught in their own, by their own factors than by a veterinarian.
DAVID BURRAGE.
Sure, absolutely.
OK, now another thing that you mentioned that stimulated me was that before World War II and even before the 1960s, as a matter of fact, more out of state were applying to Texas A&M.
And we briefly talked about this last time.
I was wondering what effect it had, what effect these out of state students had on Texas A&M.

well of course it had it had two effects first it it crowded out many potential texas students and the second it just overburdened the facilities right but with the regional boards like for example southern board uh
let nine or 12 Louisiana students come in.
Those were picked students, picked by Louisiana, not by Texas A&M, but sent over under the covering of the National Education Board, or Southern Regional, I believe they called it.
But since they were picked students, they were no dummies.
Yeah, they were top notch.
They were top notch, and that raised the IQ quite a bit.
and it raised the competition.
Sure, for Texans too.

Sure, because there were nine places that, or 12 places that were set aside for Louisiana, there were 12 places Texas couldn't get, and then when they let the girls in, that really put the big pot in the little one, because those girls were and are top students, and so
Competition is, again, keen.
So it really comes down to the fact when you take the top number of students, when you take in 128 and you have 500 applications, you have a pretty competitive deal.
In fact, it's even more competitive than it is to get into medical school, quite a bit.

Now the first woman was admitted as a student here in 1963 and now they comprise about one-third of the student body and I was wondering if there was any resistance from the faculty members when the first women came?
They might have been a little temporary resistance but there's none now.
In fact the girls are, the women I should say, are
university good students and we've progressed sufficiently far now that we have several women faculty members.
I noticed that.
Particularly in anatomy and bacteriology and virology and various disciplines that don't really cause them to be cowboys.
Right.
Now do you know how it came about that women were first admitted?
Well, yes.
Could you explain?
Well, I can't explain but I can tell you Mr.
Rudder decided they were going to come in and they did.
In other words, it was...
It was the handwriting on the wall.
It's like the CRA and women's rights and everything.
regardless of what you say, you couldn't run Texas A&M without federal money.
And women are citizens, and the daughters and even the wives of some of the veterinarians wanted to take veterinary medicine.
If they were qualified, why, what could you do?
And so it was just, it was just a part of the
coming of age or the realization that a woman is a citizen.
For example, Dr. Dorothea Robin out here at College Station, her husband was a professor, well actually he was an instructor then, in the Department of Pathology.
She was graduating University of Texas in biology, so she applied, she got her degree,
Since then, there have been quite a few male veterinarians, married women veterinarians, who set up a joint practice.
And quite a few of those role matches started in the veterinary school.
I would think so.
And to present time, I think, I'm not, you'll have to check with Dr. Shelton or Dr. Bay on this, but I think there's about 25% of the total enrollment in the school of veterinary medicine are women.
Right today, there's about one-third.
Is that right?
Well, anyway, they're almost unbearably good students and they rarely see one drop out because it's scholastic.
In other words, it was basically Mr. Rutter's decision that brought this about.
There wasn't any input from the doctors of veterinary medicine who were teaching?
Well, who makes those decisions?
I don't know.
I was just like you.
I just worked there.
Right, right.
I know, I know.
All I know, it came in during Mr.
Rudder's regime, and most of the other schools in the United States didn't have the male-only image of Texas A&M, so we were the last to get in line.
In fact, there was a girl who graduated a year ahead of me at Kansas State,
1932 and another graduated a year following me in 1934 even though they were not in my class of 33.
I see.
But who did I don't know all I know what happened during Mr.
Rudder's regime.
Okay fine uh now did this did the admittance of women as students produce any changes in the curriculum?
No, those girls do just everything that a man does as far as... Mm-hmm.
Did it produce any changes in student activities?
Was there a woman's organization of veterinarians?
There is a national organization of women veterinarians, but locally I don't know.
Okay, okay.

Now there's still something that interests me and I know last time we talked about this and last time you weren't quite sure why this was but you know in 1962 180 students applied for vet school and today there's over 600 students.
That is the mystery.
I was talking to my local physician about that the other day.
He had a relative that had a
wanted to be a veterinarian.
And he never got in, although he applied two or three times.
But he remarked, and he used a word, he said, hell, it's harder to get in veterinary school than it is in medical school.
I said, yes, or law school either.
But why, I don't know.
Why all of a sudden everybody in the United States decided they wanted to be a veterinarian, I don't know.
No.
You'll have to ask some economist or whatnot, but I really don't know.
Now, back in 1957 and 1958, in those years, there were approximately 240 students total in vet school.
And now it's over 400.
So I was wondering what impact that increase in students had.
Well, the impact was that we were always using a dollar short and a day late.
We were trying to, running all the time to stay in the same place.
But it meant that more instructors had to be hired and more physical facility had to be obtained.
And it's primarily why there's new clinical facility being built out on the highway now.
But the demand has to be there before you can sell it to the power to be to get money for teachers and buildings and equipment.
Because it comes as a surprise to a lot of people
It's almost expensive to educate a veterinarian as an individual physician.
Microscopes cost the same, x-ray machines cost the same.
Sure.
Bacteriology and virology techniques are the same.
So we were just running like hell trying to save them.
Trying to keep up with it, OK.
Now, because there were more students, did that mean that there were new programs that were developed?
No, it meant that, come back to the original statement, why were there more students?
I don't know.
The curriculum had been pretty well standardized.
Oh, occasionally they put in one class or dropped out one class, but
The curriculum's been pretty well standardized for the last 20 years.
Okay.
With the exception, of course, of moving things out of the veterinary curriculum into the pre-veterinary curriculum to make room for more clinical science.
Okay.
Now, do you think with the hiring of new instructors, do you think the quality of instruction change in any way?
Oh, if anything, it's gone better because these new instructors, most of them are graduates from top graduates from schools that had just as much pressure as we do.
Okay, so you think that the quality of instruction probably improved.
Oh, yeah.
Okay.
Now, I was wondering about something else as far as instruction.
Well, there's another thing I'd like to emphasize.
All the instructors in the School of Veterinary Medicine are not veterinarians.
For example, in bacteriology and virology and things like that, there are many PhDs.
Right, right.
Well, why don't we stay on that topic for a minute?
I was going to ask you about that.
We didn't, at Texas A&M, we didn't grant a master's degree and doctor's degree for some years.
As a matter of fact, we didn't grant our first PhD until 1955 at Texas A&M.
That's right.
Look how the graduate school has grown.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
I was wondering what was the stimulus?
What were the reasons for now expanding your program from just doctors of veterinarian medicine now to PhD in veterinarian pathology or something?
Well, I think it's primarily the demand for research and for teaching purposes.
Okay.
Because the DVM and the research laboratory, for example, National Institute of Health or whatnot,
Needs the original, needs the additional specialization in order to hold the job.
Research is a big deal when everything causes cancer that you eat.
And you have to have a hundred rats on something for a hundred days.
Somebody has to examine those rats to tell whether they're cancerous or not.
So you have to have a qualified pathologist.
or water quality, you have to have a qualified bacteriologist or biologist to isolate, for example, infectious hepatitis from the oysters that they drag up out of New Orleans.
And then we're going into things like marine biology and these fish farms where people are growing catfish in a two-acre pond on their own land.
And then, of course, there's always the fact we've had the good years when everybody had a dog and most people have a horse.
You have a boat, and if you're really uptown, well, you have a boat and you put your horse in it and go down the highway with a trailer so everybody knows you're well off.
But like the recent outbreak,
rabies care in Houston and to a lesser extent here in Bryan.
You have to have skilled people with the actual basic knowledge of how to handle things like that.
I have another question concerning people with doctorates and advanced degrees coming to Texas A&M.
In the history department some years ago there was a tendency that whenever you needed a new professor you just called up the University of Texas and
They sent over a couple of their PhD candidates and you hired one and consequently we have a number of people on our staff that were hired before 1970 that were PhDs from Texas.
Does the vet school or did the vet school favor a certain institution?
No.
Well, let me put it this way.
In the early days, Ohio State probably got the nod because of Dr. Francis.
But since 19, oh, I'd say 1920, 25, they take the best man they can get.
For example, we've had several people from the University of Iowa, from the University of California, I mean, Colorado, quite a few from Cornell, some from Georgia.
For example, a man who took my place at the university when I retired, Dr. Bell.
University of Georgia graduate.
And then, like, since all the new schools come in, we have a lot more varieties to select from.
We have people here from Purdue and from Missouri and from California, all of which were, those schools didn't exist back there.
They actually only had about six or eight schools to pick from prior to 1925.
There's another thing I was interested in with young instructors and that is the basis for tenure in the School of Veterinary Medicine.
I can't tell you that because I really don't know.
I know that professors usually get tenure or they don't, they wouldn't give a professorship but the others I don't know the number of years you have to be or
No, I'm not talking about recently.
I'm talking about when you started teaching, for example.
Were you on a tenure system in the 30s and the 40s or exactly?
Well, actually, I was in the Experiment Station the first nine years and there wasn't a tenure.
Right, you were just a staff member.
But when you switched and when new people in the 1940s and 50s came in exclusively to teach, were they on some sort of a tenure system?
Not unless they were assistant professor or higher.
And most of the time, I think it broke off with the associate professor.
But I really don't know that.
You'll have to ask somebody better qualified.
That comes under academic rules and regulations.
While we're talking about the fact that more PhDs were issued, I've noticed that the deans and the administrators invariably in the more recent years have held
held the PhD.
Has that affected, uh, quality of education?
Well, I think that's simply, uh, what you say, window dressing.
That's not the right word, but it's pretty hard to impress a PhD unless you have one also.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
Or judge his qualifications.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
But it's all come back to the fact that
Most of those fellows who were dean now weren't counting on being dean when they got to Ph.D.
They were figuring they were going into research or teaching or something similar.
Industrial research has a lot of those names.
People who put out that Merck manual have got a lot of names.
Mischart and Dohm and those kind of people.
I mean, Merck, Sharp, and Dohm.
Do these advanced degrees have any connection with an increasing amount of specialization in veterinary medicine?
Is veterinary medicine becoming more specialized like so many other endeavors?
In fact, we have subdivisions in the AVMA.
We have the Society of Equine Practitioners, Association of Bovine Practitioners, Association of Swine Practitioners.
Association of Industrial Veterinarians.
Oh, you can go on, you can subdivide it down to, almost divide it to MDs, except we don't have any pediatrics yet, or gynecologists.
Now there's something else I was interested in, and that is the Southwestern Veterinarian, the journal.
Well... Do you know anything about that?
I do.
I was one of the instigators on starting it.
Good.
Tell me about your role, your participation in that.
Well, the students, some of these better students that we talked about earlier, felt that we should have a medium by which they could write things or learn how to present research, either profound or
less so, and some of the practitioners in the state were, most of whom were recent graduates, also wanted to help us.
At that time, the Texas Veterinary Medical General, which is the official organ of the state thing, was just really a news sheet.
It wasn't a general in the sense of word, and

was also on the editorial board of that and we decided that we would keep the official publication simply that not try to make it a general in the true sense of words like for example the general the avma or what so forth first because of cost come out of practitioners pocket second if we
had to pay for articles and things and whatnot, the printing and so forth.
The description would be so high, which now goes as part of their dues, that it would have a negative effect.
So they were wholeheartedly behind the Southwestern Bandai.
And the first boy we had as editor, his name was Carl Wallace, I believe, fell to the cave.
proved quite apt, and we got off to a good start.
And it was primarily designed as a magazine for practicing veterinary.
Instead of having some article there on the effect of some rare drug on monkeys,
or how to extract the tooth from an Indian elephant.
It was down-to-earth, everyday practice problems.
And it succeeded beyond our expectations.
And then, of course, the...
In what way?
In acceptance by the profession.
And then inflation caught us.
There was one else.
And we had a little trouble financially.
When was this?
Well, the last few years.
The last few years, OK. Because the price of paper went up.
Sure.
Price of printing went up.
And so the price in general had to go up.
And there's a little consumer resistance, like everything else.
You don't need as much butter for $2 a pound if you do it.
twenty-five cents, but so far it weathered the storm.
But it was primarily started by the students, and the former graduates of this school have been most faithful in helping keep it up.
Now what was your role?
More advisory?
Advisory.
It was a student publication.
Yeah, right.
They were, I forget, three or five faculty members that served on the advisory committee together with the director of student publications.
Now that we're talking about your duties and functions, from 1949 until 1967, you were on the library committee.
15 years.
Could you tell me about that?
Yes.
It started with our move across, no it didn't, it started while we were still on the main campus.
Dr. Ralph Dunn was dean then and we had a spare room in the veterinary hospital.
Dr. Marksteller had a few issues of his blood horse
Gentile journals and various trade journals.
The boys used it primarily as a place to go in and smoke a cigarette and spend spare time between classes.
So Dr. Dunn came up with the idea, why don't we start a library?
And in order for it to be viable and functional,
to not be in competition with Cushing Memorial, but be a part of it.
So he talked to, I forget who the librarian was over there at that time.
We were in charge of the main library.
But it was agreeable.
And we had asked each department to contribute books
that time each department bought their own books, you see.
Where'd they keep them?
They kept them in their own individual offices.
See, there wasn't any central library.
In other words, in the clinic would be books on clinical medicine, and the pathology department would be pathology, and so forth.
So they agreed, and it just grew, it just started to grow.
our first, I can't think of her name, anyway, we got a professionally trained librarian.
What was, pardon me, turn it off.
June, what was, anyway, we obtained a professional medical librarian, and one who was familiar
technical words and technical phrases and she got it off to a real good start and she was offered a better job in Houston or someplace and we brought in a Mrs. Kirksey, K-I-R-K-S-E.
